4165247;R for Absolute Beginners - ONLINE;FALSE;2024-02-01T12:00:00Z;2024-02-01T14:00:00Z;"

R is a general programming language
column2: especially suited for statistical analysis and cleaning and visualization of data.

column1: We assume absolutely no previous experience with programming
column2: and will cover the basics of getting started with R
and how to interact with R
variables and objects

column1: • Simple arithmetic and logical operations on data
• Working with functions - and how to write a very simple function ourself
<li>And how to make a couple of the common graphs
column2: that are as useful as they are elementary.
we recommend that you either download and install R and RStudio
column3: or register for an account at rstudio.cloud. Instructions on this can be found here
column4: where you will also find the course notes

column1:
Please note that this course will be held in english if any participants requests it. Otherwise it will be held in danish.

4141101;Explorative data analysis with R;FALSE;2024-02-05T09:00:00Z;2024-02-05T11:00:00Z;"

How do you gain insight in your data? We explore a largish dataset using statistical methods and visualizations.
We assume that you have some experience working with R
column2: and knows the tidyverse. The level required is what you would learn on one of our introductory course in "R for absolute beginners".

column1: You should have R and Rstudio installed before the course
column2: and preferably also have downloaded the dataset that we are going to explore. You can find further instructions here.

column1:
The course is by default held in Danish - unless one or more participants requests us to do it in English.

column1: 4132925;NVivo - Introduction to Qualitative Data Analysis Software (QDAS) (English);FALSE;2024-02-07T09:00:00Z;2024-02-07T11:30:00Z;"
Introduction to NVivo; a program which is a great help when you are working with qualitative data analysis.

column2: if you want to organise and/or code your empirical material or literature. It can also be helpful when you want to transcribe audio- or video files

column1: The PC version of NVivo has more functionality than the Mac version
column2: but you can participate in all exercises with either and we will demonstrate in both.
you must install the version of NVivo called NVivo 14.

column1: This can be done here for Windows:
Registration key is available through the UCPH Software Library.
Please note: NVivo can be found int the Software Library under the link "QSR International - NVivo".
We also ask you to complete a set of introductory exercises before course start
column2: that you can read about HERE.

column1: The course requires a minimum of six participants.

/Erik Schwägermann (es@kb.dk) og Daniel Pryn (pryn@kb.dk)

Introduction to NVivo; a program which is a great help when you are working with qualitative data analysis.

column2: if you want to organise and/or code your empirical material or literature. It can also be helpful when you want to transcribe audio- or video files

column1: The PC version of NVivo has more functionality than the Mac version
column2: but you can participate in all exercises with either and we will demonstrate in both.
you must install the version of NVivo called NVivo 14.

column1: This can be done here for Windows:

column1:
4183100;Digital Humaniora - tekst som data;FALSE;2024-02-28T08:30:00Z;2024-02-28T11:00:00Z;"

** For English see below **

Kurset "Introduktion til Digital Humaniora med fokus på tekst som data" giver mulighed at opnå en forståelse for begreber som "text mining" og "distant reading". På kurset tager vi udgangspunkt i brugervenlige programmer og hjemmesider. Vi kigger på avanceret brug af Google Ngram Viewer for at få en forståelse for distant reading og big data. Vi bruger Orange til at indsamle tekster fra The Guardian og Wikipedia
column2: og vi taler nogle almindelige algoritmer til text mining på store datasæt. Med udgangspunkt i Voyant og Spyral forholder vi os til algoritmer og grafer til at gå i dybden med mindre tekstsamlinger.

column1: • distant reading med udgangspunkt i Google Ngram
• dataindsamling og analyse med udgangspunkt i Orange
• visualiseringer og formidling med udgangspunkt Voyant Tools og Spyral

column2: 5 timer med to korte pauser og veksler mellem korte oplæg efterfulgt af små øvelser.  Kurset foregår på KUB Søndre Campus i datalabbet på anden sal.
hvis der er deltagere på kurset

column1: The course "Introduction to Digital Humanities with a focus on text as data" offers an opportunity to gain an understanding of concepts such as "text mining" and "distant reading". In this course
column2: we will start with user-friendly programs and websites. We will look at advanced use of Google Ngram Viewer to understand distant reading and big data. We will use Orange to collect texts from The Guardian and Wikipedia
column3: and we will discuss some common algorithms for text mining on large datasets. With a basis in Voyant and Spyral
column4: we will delve into algorithms and graphs to go in depth with smaller text collections.

column1: • Distant reading with a basis in Google Ngram
• Data collection and analysis with a basis in Orange
• Visualizations and dissemination with a basis in Voyant Tools and Spyral
The course lasts 2.5 hours with two short breaks and alternates between brief lectures followed by small exercises. The course takes place at KUB Southern Campus in the data lab on the second floor.
The course will be conducted in English if there are participants who do not speak Danish.

Translated from Danish to English using AI.

column2: Karen Blixens Plads 7

column1: The course "Introduction to Digital Humanities with a focus on text as data" offers an opportunity to gain an understanding of concepts such as "text mining" and "distant reading". In this course
column2: we will start with user-friendly programs and websites. We will look at advanced use of Google Ngram Viewer to understand distant reading and big data. We will use Orange to collect texts from The Guardian and Wikipedia
column3: and we will discuss some common algorithms for text mining on large datasets. With a basis in Voyant and Spyral
column4: we will delve into algorithms and graphs to go in depth with smaller text collections.

column1: • Distant reading with a basis in Google Ngram
• Data collection and analysis with a basis in Orange
• Visualizations and dissemination with a basis in Voyant Tools and Spyral
The course lasts 2.5 hours with two short breaks and alternates between brief lectures followed by small exercises. The course takes place at KUB Southern Campus in the data lab on the second floor.
The course will be conducted in English if there are participants who do not speak Danish.

Translated from Danish to English using AI.

** For English see below **

Kurset "Introduktion til Digital Humaniora med fokus på tekst som data" giver mulighed at opnå en forståelse for begreber som "text mining" og "distant reading". På kurset tager vi udgangspunkt i brugervenlige programmer og hjemmesider. Vi kigger på avanceret brug af Google Ngram Viewer for at få en forståelse for distant reading og big data. Vi bruger Orange til at indsamle tekster fra The Guardian og Wikipedia
column2: og vi taler nogle almindelige algoritmer til text mining på store datasæt. Med udgangspunkt i Voyant og Spyral forholder vi os til algoritmer og grafer til at gå i dybden med mindre tekstsamlinger.

column1: • distant reading med udgangspunkt i Google Ngram
• dataindsamling og analyse med udgangspunkt i Orange
• visualiseringer og formidling med udgangspunkt Voyant Tools og Spyral
Kurset tager tre timer med to korte pauser og veksler mellem korte oplæg efterfulgt af små øvelser.  Kurset foregår på KUB Søndre Campus i datalabbet på anden sal.

column2: hvis der er deltagere på kurset

column1: The course "Introduction to Digital Humanities with a focus on text as data" offers an opportunity to gain an understanding of concepts such as "text mining" and "distant reading". In this course
column2: we will start with user-friendly programs and websites. We will look at advanced use of Google Ngram Viewer to understand distant reading and big data. We will use Orange to collect texts from The Guardian and Wikipedia
column3: and we will discuss some common algorithms for text mining on large datasets. With a basis in Voyant and Spyral
column4: we will delve into algorithms and graphs to go in depth with smaller text collections.

column1: • Distant reading with a basis in Google Ngram
• Data collection and analysis with a basis in Orange
• Visualizations and dissemination with a basis in Voyant Tools and Spyral

The course lasts three hours with two short breaks and alternates between brief lectures followed by small exercises. The course takes place at KUB Southern Campus in the data lab on the second floor.
The course will be conducted in English if there are participants who do not speak Danish.

column2: if you want to organise and/or code your empirical material or literature. It can also be helpful when you want to transcribe audio- or video files

4175641;Text Mining with R;FALSE;2024-04-18T08:00:00Z;2024-04-18T10:00:00Z;"

In this course you will learn how to use text mining techniques with the programming language R to gain insights in to a large number of texts. Text mining is a set of powerful tools that allow you to make sense of a large set of texts and gain insights that are hard to spot by just reading the text yourself. You will also learn how to visualize your findings to showcase your results.
We will use summaries from the debates in the Danish parliament (Folketinget) as our data
column2: but the tools and techniques that you learn can be used for text mining any set of texts.

column1: You don't need any experience with text mining
column2: but participants should have a basic knowledge about R
column3: corresponding to our introductory course "R for Absolute Beginners". You must also have downloaded and installed R and Rstudio. Instructions on this can be found here

column1:
Please note that this course will be held in English if any participants request it. Otherwise it will be held in Danish.

4182799;Searching for open data: Strategies and pitfalls;FALSE;2024-05-15T08:00:00Z;2024-05-15T09:30:00Z;"

Digital resources abound
column2: but some are trickier to find and use than others
column3: none more so than open data
column4: which can be reused for new research projects.  In this course
column5: we will put together some broad strategies for searching for open and accessible data
column6: which can help to build up your research projects.  We will also cover issues in information literacy
column8: and trust when searching for data.  The session will end with a workshop
column9: where attendees can either search for data that can butress an ongoing project
column10:
or they can search for supporting data to a couple of potential research questions to train the newly acquired strategies.  Information specialists will be on hand to guide and advise your searches.
